  <!-- Definition -->
  <section class="section alt">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Definition: Edge Computing</h2>

      <div class="definition-box">
        <p><strong>Edge computing</strong> is the practice of processing and storing data closer to the source (the "edge") rather than at centralized data centers.</p>

        <ul class="definition-points">
          <li><strong>The Edge:</strong> Data centers physically located near where data is generated or consumed (at the network edge)</li>
          <li><strong>The Cloud:</strong> Centralized data centers far from most users (usually 1-2 central locations per region)</li>
          <li><strong>Distributed:</strong> Instead of 1-2 data centers per region, hundreds to thousands of edge locations worldwide</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <p>Think of it like this: instead of shipping goods from a warehouse across the country (cloud), you have distribution centers in every city (edge).</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Why It Matters -->
